observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the City Mayor agreed to direct the General Services Officer to:

a.	Conduct the physical count of PPE in accordance with the procedural guidelines enumerated in COA Circular No. 2020-006;

b.	Prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) and conduct reconciliation with that of the Accounting records to facilitate the identification of discrepancies and adjust the errors noted; and

c.	Classify assets that did not meet the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 and those that have no costs


We also recommended and the City Mayor agreed to direct the City Accountant to:

a. 	Prepare adjusting entry/ies to reclassify assets that did not meet the capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00;

b. 	Ensure that transactions are properly classified in accordance with the prescribed Chart of Accounts for Local Government Units;

c. 	Review the supporting schedules, identify those items that were                     misclassified and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct the balances in the books;


d. 	Identify PPEs that were acquired in CY 2011 and prior years that have already exhausted their estimated useful life to aid Management’s decision on whether these will be disposed of or continued to be used in the operations of the City; and

e. 	Extend effort in the identification of PPEs classified as Other Assets that were acquired in CY 1994 and prior years and disclosed in the Notes to the Financial Statements.

Furthermore, we recommended that the City Mayor submit a request for authority to derecognize the PPEs acquired in CY 1994 and prior years following the procedures provided by COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the Management ensure that all PPEs included in the Inventory Report are duly recorded in the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the GSO and reconciled with the PPELCs maintained by the Accounting Unit in accordance with 6.3 of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended the submission of justification for the mentioned deficiencies noted, as follows:

For giving so much leeway to the supplier/contractor by not including in the contract the required total quantity, specification of materials, scope of work and the date of completion;

For not enforcing damages for the delay in the deliveries of materials;

For submitting two Acceptance and Inspection Report with a different date of acceptance.

Moreover, we also recommended the submission of the mentioned documents as required under Republic Act No. 9003 dated January 26, 2001, known as the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000, and Republic Act No. 9184 and its IRR-A, known as the Government Procurement Reform Act. Henceforth, management should strictly comply with Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and Section IV of COA Circular No. 97-004 dated July 1, 1997 requiring submission of complete documentation and proper evidence on all classes of disbursements. Likewise, management should strictly comply with the criteria set under Republic Act No. 9003 dated January 26, 2001, known as the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000, and other pertinent laws and regulations on Solid Waste Management as well as with Republic Act No. 9184 and its IRR-A on its procurement process.

